r units, and logistical support roles.</li>\n<li><strong>Navy:</strong> Around 60,000 African Americans served in the Navy. Initially relegated to menial roles such as stewards and cooks, black sailors gradually expanded into technical and combat-related positions as the war progressed.</li>\n<li><strong>Army Air Forces:</strong> Approximately 15,000 African Americans served in the Army Air Forces. The most notable group, the Tuskegee Airmen, broke racial barriers as fighter pilots and bomber crews.</li>\n<li><strong>Marine Corps:</strong> Before 1942, African Americans were excluded from the Marines. Upon integration, roughly 20,000 black Marines served by the end of the war.</li>\n<li><strong>Coast Guard:</strong> Around 2,000 African American personnel served, often in support and logistical roles.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>The Social and Military Impact of Black Soldiers in WWII</h2>\n<p>The presence of black soldiers in World War II was a catalyst for change both within the military and in American society. Despite the segregation and systemic racism they encountered, their service challenged prevailing stereotypes and laid the groundwork for desegregation efforts in the armed forces, culminating in President Truman’s Executive Order 9981 in 1948.</p>\n<h3>Combat Roles and Notable Units</h3>\n<p>While many black servicemen were relegated to non-combat roles, several units earned distinction on the battlefield:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>The Tuskegee Airmen:</strong> This group of African American pilots and support crew was instrumental in escorting bombers over Europe, earning an outstanding combat record and disproving myths about black soldiers’ capabilities.</li>\n<li><strong>The 92nd Infantry Division (“Buffalo Soldiers”):</strong> One of the few predominantly black combat units, the 92nd fought in the Italian Campaign, demonstrating valor under challenging conditions.</li>\n<li><strong>The 761st Tank Battalion:</strong> Known as the “Black Panthers,” this unit partici